messages.content: @DrP | SN(21,24) would you be able to help with this question?

You can access the dataset here: https://huggingface.co/datasets/omegalabsinc/omega-multimodal which has an MIT license allowing for fairly unrestricted access.
I'm not a lawyer, but I suspect in this case it's probably ok to use the data, regardless of copyright, because it's not a republication of the content or even directly using the audio/video/text, rather it's metadata and embeddings. That is, you wouldn't be able to use the data to recreate the original content with any sort of fidelity (at least not yet).
Also, at least in the US, the concept of "fair use" for training AIs may offer some legal protections, although there are pending lawsuits regarding just that, so it's hard to say exactly where the line will be drawn.
It's actually impossible to build AI models of any quality without copyrighted data (when I scraped the top 5k domains by traffic, only 18.56% didn't have an obviously posted copyright notice), so this fair use exemption is quite critical.
That said, if you wanted to use the dataset commercially or for any other purpose that may surface copyright concerns, I would hire a lawyer and/or just find different means of training the model.

Hey OMEGA miners

**Update on the current emissions situation**
- The change that we put out where validators punish miners who don't respond was meant to punish miners who just stop responding entirely. Without penalizing such miners, emissions were unfairly being distributed to miners who don't do any work. Whether there were any such miners or not, fixing that loophole was an important priority to keep the system robust.
- Unfortunately, this also had the unintended consequence of punishing miners who have not optimized their miner code for being able to handle concurrent requests. We care about quality over quantity and so it's our goal to reward the highest quality data (within a reasonable time frame like 90 seconds) rather than encouraging miners to maximize their throughput. I anticipate that as the subnet matures more and more, mosts miners should be able to load balance and handle multiple requests at once, as quality AND quantity are possible together by loadbalancing well.
- Many miners have complained about seeing successful scrape logs and yet being penalized in the validator logs. This is likely because when the validator makes a request to you, their timeout clock starts ticking. However, a miner's clock only starts ticking after the miner has started working on the request. Suppose a miner receives Request A and starts working on it and then gets Request B after 5 seconds. Suppose they respond to request A within 70 seconds and then request B another 70 seconds after that. Technically, the miner thinks they responded to Request B in 70 seconds, but really, from the validator's perspective, they took 70 + 70 - 5 = 135 seconds. The increased 120 second timeout helps here, but is sometimes still not enough.
- Note that some validators likely still haven't updated which is causing miners to be bombarded with an unreasonable amount of concurrent requests, so the subnet is kind of in a transitory state.

**Next steps for me and for miners**
- I think the most reasonable course of action is to reduce the penalty of -0.005 to just a 0 score or even a 0.005 minimum emissions. This way, unproductive miners would have super low emissions, reasonable miners would have decent emissions, and well parallelized miners would have excellent emissions.
- There ought to be a way for miners to ensure that they respond within the deadline time from when they first received the request, rather than from when they start working on a request. This is important for miners to conserve their resources and avoid working on a task which they won't get emissions for anyways. I will try adding this to the base miner code.
- I will add a validator auto-updating script to make it easy for validators to integrate the latest changes as we'll probably need to experiment with the incentive structure a bit to land on the optimal balance between the quality-quantity trade-off.

    - **Zero-Shot Personalization**: Have the model understand input modalities so well that it can **create faithful representations in new modalities**
